post_text:
CHANGE IN SCHOOL START DATE

The West Burlington Independent School District Board of Education held an emergency meeting earlier this afternoon to discuss options for reopening school.

Due to the continued increase in the 14 day positivity rate for Des Moines county the start of school has been delayed until August 31st. The positivity rate as of 10:30 am this morning was 15.4%, the 3rd highest in the state of Iowa.

The board will meet on Wednesday, August 26th to determine how it will reopen school on Monday, the 31st.

Parents need to be prepared for reopening under a totally virtual model or under an A/B model..

At this time high school activities will continue to practice. Junior high activities will not start practice until the start of school. Participation in scheduled games/scrimmages will be determined on an event by event basis.

Chromebooks will be distributed next week as a preparatory measure.

More information and details will follow next week about the district’s reopening on August 31st.

post_text:
Dear Parents,
Attached please find information about the virtual option of learning. This document serves to lay out the broad expectations for students who will be participating in school through a remote setting as well as for all students on Fridays. They are also the expectations for all students should the district need to move a class, building or district to a virtual setting for their learning.

Should you have questions about these expectations and other questions specific to your students grade level, please feel free to contact the building principals.

Students who will be starting school in the virtual setting should plan to pick up their Chromebooks, should they need one, on either Friday or Monday. Building principals will communicate the times and details to this pick up prior to Friday. Should you have your own device to use, please contact the building secretary and let them know.

Students who will be attending face-to-face instruction will receive their Chromebook on the first day of school.

Lisa Beames
Superintendent

After conferring with three different weather applications, We are moving forward with the Graduation ceremony outside @ 2:00. Please bring your yard sign and lawn chairs. There are 54 circles painted on the field for the graduates' families. Gates are open to come plant your sign.

WEST BURLINGTON GRADUATION CEREMONY, June 20 2020 @ 2:00

Graduation practice, Friday June 19 @ 9:30 am. Meet in the Auditorium for directions.

Gates to the stadium will be opened by 11:00 am for families to choose their sitting areas on the football field.

We will make the decision Saturday morning at about 10 am if we will have to move the ceremony indoors. A final announcement will go out that morning about if the ceremony will be outside or inside. Check our social media sources for updates. In the event of inclement weather Saturday, the ceremony will be moved to the High School Gym.

Due to seating capacity limits, each graduate will be allowed 6 ticketed guests. Graduates will be given the tickets for their guests during the graduation practice.

Individuals without tickets will not be allowed to attend. We are sorry to implement this, however it must be done in order to maintain the 50% seating capacity limit.

post_text:
As parents and guardians, you may be struggling to find the right words to talk to your children about what is happening across the nation. Our children may be seeing and hearing things that they might not understand. These are heavy but important topics for our children that we must address with thoughtfulness and intention. There is no better time to talk about what is happening in the nation and to help our children comprehend what they are seeing and hearing as well as how they can make a difference. Below, are two guides to help you talk to your children about hate and racism. Feel free to use them if you are struggling to find the words on where to begin. But please, take the time to find the words, listen, ask questions and have those conversations.

Darkness cannot drive out darkness; only light can do that. Hate cannot drive out hate; only love can do that. ~ Martin Luther King, Jr.

Be an example of light, love and peace, Falcon Family!

https://www.parents.com/…/how-to-teach-your-kids-to-fight…/…

https://www.parenttoolkit.com/…/how-to-talk-to-kids-about-r…

post_text:
After great deliberation it has been determined that prom will not be rescheduled. We appreciate and empathize with the many emotions tied to this decision and hope that you can appreciate the difficulty of this decision.

Our ultimate goal is to keep everyone as safe as possible while moving forward with school and life within the guidelines before us.

While various potential options were considered, ultimately it was not believed that it is realistically possible to maintain the current and foreseeable social distancing expectations for such a large number of students.

On behalf of the district and it's administration please know that we all embrace your feelings of loss.

Regretfully,

Lisa Beames

Throughout the last few weeks, we have seen so many actions and displays of perseverance, amazing hearts, creative minds, kindness, love, appreciation, thankfulness, and selfless acts from our own people here in West Burlington and others across the world! It’s amazing to see so many people letting their lights shine so brightly to bring smiles and happiness to everyone around them during this time. I am so excited to share the song “Be A Light” with you all, performed by our very own bright light Mr. Wagner. Now and always, Be a Light to others Falcon Friends! Please comment on our post with a picture or a phrase of how you are being a light during this time! Let's keep encouraging each others! #falconfamily #weareinthistogehter 🖤💚

A West Burlington Staff Parade is coming to town! On Monday, March 30th, beginning at 5:30 p.m., staff members will be making their way through the streets of West Burlington to wave and say hi to our families! WE MISS YOU! DURING SCHOOL CLOSURE

Starting Monday, March 23rd, free meals will be provided to children under 18 years of age.

Sites include West Burlington Elementary, North Hill Elementary in Burlington and Burlington Community High School.

You do not have to be enrolled in the respective district to receive a meal.

Please see attached flyer for more information.

Please complete the survey below by Friday, March 20th at noon so we may have an estimate of meals to have available.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfi-HkP0iKTZhzXIigoosRVwKQGlXYxGAywGcZSY1oM2X2PWw/viewform

Governor Kim Reynolds has recommended school closures. A press conference will be held tomorrow with further details.

WBISD will be closed starting tomorrow, March 16, 2020. Further updates and information about learning and lunches will be communicated tomorrow
No staff are to report to school as well.

See the https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FKAXj9Wa1utQLZyLE4qFyucGCueKsAHf76eCVUVd-vA/view attached for additional information

Thank you for your patience and support as we maneuver these unchartered waters.

Lisa Beames
Superintendent

shared_text:
Iowa Wesleyan University is with Mariska Malloy.
March 6 at 2:15 PM ·

On Thursday, eleven teams of middle school students from across southeast Iowa gathered on the IW campus to compete in the first Wesley’s Math Challenge. The challenge’s top prizes went to the teams from the West Burlington Independent School District in first place, Cardinal Community School District in second place, and MP Middle School in third. CONGRATS to all who participated!

post_text:
In consultation with local law enforcement, due to an ongoing community situation students will not be allowed to walk home this afternoon. This is solely a precautionary measure.

Parents/Guardians who may need to pick their students up early may begin to do so at 2:30 from the respective building offices with school remaining in session until the usual release time.

Students will not be released early without a parent/guardian picking them up.

The elementary pick-up lanes will be utilized as usual.

Secondary students who have driven will be released at usual time.

Elementary students with older siblings transporting them will be escorted to the high school and released to their sibling as usual.

Students utilizing the city bus will be walked by a staff member.

The YMCA program will be held as usual.

Please follow these directions and any other directions of staff and please be patient as we work to have an orderly release.

The school as well as the local law enforcement deem the safety of our students as one of our highest priorities. It has been and is forefront in our decision making processes today as the police work through a challenging situation.

The West Burlington Independent Schools is operating as usual with all students and staff going about their daily routines.

The school and local law enforcement will continue to work together to ensure the ongoing safety of our students and staff.

The district will communicate promptly with parents should the situation change.

Dear Parents/Guardians and Students, The Fifth-grade class is asking your help in making someone else’s holiday season a little better! We are collecting non- perishable food items and personal hygiene items for Kayla’s Cupboard. Students need to bring their items/ canned goods to their classroom teachers.

We will collect items from now until December 18. Below you will find a list of items needed at Kayla’s Cupboard. Every little donation helps!

-Thank you. Mrs. Henry, Mr. Nehring, Mrs. Schmidt, and Mrs. Shipp

Suggested Donation Items Include:
Baby Food, Baby Diapers, Canned Dinners (Ravioli, Chili, Spaghetti-O’s), Instant Mixes (Potatoes, Pancakes, Bread, Cakes), Canned Meats (Tuna, Chicken, etc.), Peanut Butter Jelly/Jam, Uncooked Pasta Noodles, Canned/Jarred Pasta Sauce, Macaroni & Cheese, Boxed or Bagged Cereals, Pop-Tarts, Instant Coffee, Canned/Boxed Soup, Crackers, Juice Boxes, Popcorn, Chips, Paper Products, Hand Soap and Sanitizer, Shampoo, Body Wash, Toothpaste and Toothbrushes, any personal hygiene item.

post_text:
Notice: Junior High Student Council is hosting a food drive for the West Burlington Food Pantry starting November 4 - 19, 2019. The food drive will be accepting donations of can goods, dry goods, boxed goods and paper products. Foods most needed to donate are canned vegetables, canned soup,canned meat,canned beans, peanut butter, canned fruit, boxes of rice,pasta and paper towels and toilet paper. Perishable items such as fresh foods will not be accepted.

In addition to this food drive,student council will also be holding a competition between 6th, 7th and 8th grade. The winning grade that brings the most food will celebrate with a pizza party for that grade on a date to be determined,after the completion of the food drive..

Food can be brought to Ms. Bourg's Room 383 each day during the contest and will be placed in the grade level box. Food will be accepted through the end of the day, November 18th,2019.
